arch:property.oc:show_val: This locus is a mudbrick wall that is not well preserved. It is abutted by an ashy layer (L6, L8, L13, L14) on the south side of the wall. There are at least 2 kinds of mudbricks, red brown flakey clay soil with white specks, a light green flakey clay. The colors are organized by course, 1 course red, one course green. We found this wall when cutting sections out of the NW corner of the top step of the step trench. While cutting down the wall we realized that the foundation was hard packed clay fill, L17 similar to L14 directly adjacent, and that the wall did not continue all the way to the east baulk it stops about .30m from it. The wall runs straight west to east beginning at the west baulk, see top plan part two from 7/23/02 for my interpretation of what the wall looked like.
hard flaky pink bricks (clayey loam) with white specks of fill, hard crumbling yellow bricks
this is a mudbrick wall with at least three different colored bricks in each course

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.
